# Overview

Through the Lines is an open dataset and lookup tool. Given a street address, it returns 
every U.S. congressional district that address has belonged to across redistricting cycles, 
annotated with who drew each map, whether it was later struck down, and who represented it.

## Background

Congressional district boundaries are redrawn at least once per decade, and they determine which
candidates a voter chooses among and how their communities are represented. Who draws those lines,
and how, is the subject of continuous litigation. Revisions between censuses are becoming increasingly
common.

The 2025–2026 cycle has been an unusually active one. Beginning with
[Texas in mid-2025](https://www.cfr.org/articles/gerrymandering-the-supreme-court-and-the-2026-midterm-elections),
several states redrew their congressional maps mid-decade, a practice that is
legal but, until recently, was relatively rare. Commonly referred to as a "race
to the bottom", redistricting is increasingly polarizing, with a new map in one state
prompting counter-maps in another.

Against that backdrop, a basic question is harder to answer than it should be:
how has the district covering a particular address changed over time, and who was
responsible for each change? The raw data exists (historical district
boundaries, member records, and narrative accounts of how each plan was drawn and
litigated) but they live in separate places and separate formats, and none of
them alone answers the question at the level of one address across multiple
cycles. Through the Lines joins them into a single address-first, longitudinal
record with a structured, machine-readable layer describing each plan's origin
and legal history. 

For a more comprehensive picture of the history and mechanics behind redistricting, check
out Justin Levitt's [Redistricting 101](https://redistricting.lls.edu/redistricting-101/).

## What it provides

For a given address, Through the Lines shows the district for each Congress in
range, the incumbent who served it, the plan that drew it, the body responsible, 
and the court rulings that enabled or invalidated it. The underlying plan metadata 
is published as a citable dataset.

For how the lookup works, see [How it works](/docs/how-it-works). For current
coverage and what is planned, see [Roadmap](/docs/roadmap). For data sources and
licensing, see the [Data](/data) page.
